$\text{toBoundedBilin}(s, f)(x, y) = \int_{s} f(z) \, dE_{a}(x, y)(z)$,
where $E_{a}$ is the resolution of identity associated with the operator $a$.

For the specific case of an indicator function $\chi_s$ (where $\chi_s(x) = 1$ if $x \in s$ and $\chi_s(x) = 0$ otherwise), $\text{toBoundedBilin}(s, \chi_s)$ is the projection operator $P(s)$.

So we need to prove that $P(w_1 \cap w_2) = P(w_1) \cdot P(w_2)$.

Let's think about this algebraically. The projection operator $P(s)$ is defined as $\int_{s} \delta(z) \, dE_{a}(z)$, where $\delta(z)$ is the Dirac delta function at $z$. Then, for $P(w_1 \cap w_2)$, we have $\int_{w_1 \cap w_2} \delta(z) \, dE_{a}(z)$.

The right-hand side is $P(w_1) \cdot P(w_2) = \left(\int_{w_1} \delta(z) \, dE_{a}(z)\right) \cdot \left(\int_{w_2} \delta(z) \, dE_{a}(z)\right)$.

In general, for projection operators, we have $P(s \cap t) = P(s) \cdot P(t)$ when $s$ and $t$ are measurable sets. This is because the projection operators commute and are idempotent ($P(s)^2 = P(s)$).

