`continuousLinearMapOfBilin (@toBoundedBilin H _ _ _ a ha 1 ((w₁ ∩ w₂).indicator 1)) = continuousLinearMapOfBilin (@toBoundedBilin H _ _ _ a ha 1 (w₁.indicator 1)) * continuousLinearMapOfBilin (@toBoundedBilin H _ _ _ a ha 1 (w₂.indicator 1))`

This is equivalent to showing that the integral of the indicator function of `w₁ ∩ w₂` is the product of the integrals of the indicator functions of `w₁` and `w₂`. 

In other words, we need to prove that `∫_{w₁ ∩ w₂} 1 dE = (∫_{w₁} 1 dE) * (∫_{w₂} 1 dE)`, where `E` is the projection-valued measure associated with the self-adjoint operator `a`.

This is a standard property of projection-valued measures, specifically that the measure of the intersection of two measurable sets is the product of the measures of the individual sets. This is because the projection-valued measure is a multiplicative function on the algebra of measurable sets.

